Discovering Stories by Topic Modeling¶

I give an overview of stories covered in the twitter collection using topic modeling and clustering tweets together as stories. Steps to create clusters of tweets that are less noisy and more informative, including:

  • divided my twitter collection into time slices of one week.
  • Noise and common word removal
  • Tweet tokenizing using NLTK
  • TFIDF
  • Topic modeling(Latent Semantic Analysis)
  • added a probability threshold to further remove the noise tweets in each cluster.

An interesting fact in stories of 1st week (Topic #2) is about dress code employee policy which seems to have tweets about the event that two girls were prohibited to board because they were wearing leggings. When you investigate more, you will notice that the girls had United employee tickets and for that ticket you need to have a formal dress code.

Also, I can see that the UA incident (dragging a man out of UA airplane) has been dominant for at least two weeks. On the other hand, we dont see this pattern for AA incident. I predict that until UA and the passenger reach a settlement, the discussions on twitter will be continued. I can further investigate this in the next stage of my capstone project.

    arr1 = s.index.get_level_values(1)=='Topic #1'
    arr2 = s.index.get_level_values(0)=='4th week: April 16 - April 22'
    is_highlight = arr1 & arr2

The Most Common Phrases¶

The purpose here is to improve our understanding of the events, and get some insight from the tweets by just looking at their common bigrams, trigrams and ngrams for both UA and AA tweets. As you can see in the following plots, for UA related tweets, the word random and passenger can be seen in most common bigram, trigram and (n-4)grams. Also, we can see that most of these common phrases are related to the UA incident.

Plot #5: American Airlines Most Common Bigrams, Trigrams, (N=4)grams¶

When looking at AA common bigrams, trigrams and ngrams, we see that the number of these phrases are much fewer than the common phrases in UA dataset. Although there are common phrases like hit attendant in this dataset as well, but most of the common phrases are regular and not extreme negative tweets. Also, the number of common phrases and their sentiment, does not suggest a crisis is happening to this airlines. For future, I am planning to do Named Entity Recognition to be able to find names like oscar munoz together for the topic representative words and common phrases.
